<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec1-342-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Section 1.3/1.4/2.2</title>
  <definition xml:id="def-linear-function">
    <title>Linear Function</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>linear function</term> is a function which can be written in the form
        <md>
          f(x) = ax + b
        </md>
        where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <definition xml:id="def-intercepts">
    <title>Intercepts</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An <term>intercept</term> is the location where a function crosses an axis.
      </p>
      <p>
        An <term><m>x-</m>intercept</term> is an input where the function crosses the <m>x-</m>axis, and a <term><m>y-</m>intercept</term> is an output where the function crosses the <m>y-</m>axis.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <note xml:id="sec1-342-2-intercepts-note-1">
    <p>
      Because <m>x-</m>intercepts occur when a function crosses the <m>x-</m>axis, this means that all outputs are zero. In particular, this means that all <m>x-</m>intercepts are solutions to the equation <m>f(x) = 0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Similarly, the <m>y-</m>intercept occurs at <m>y = f(0)</m> because the input is 0 along the <m>y-</m>axis. A function can only have <alert>one</alert> <m>y-</m>intercept by definition of a function (see <xref ref="def-function"/>).
    </p>
  </note>

  <definition xml:id="def-slope">
    <title>Slope</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>slope</term> of a linear function is defined as the ratio of vertical change to horizontal change. This can be understood to be "rise over run" of the function.
      </p>
      <p>
        The slope of a linear equation <m>y = ax + b</m> is the value of the constant <m>a</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <definition xml:id="def-constant-roc">
    <title>Constant Rate of Change</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>constant rate of change</term> of a linear function is the value of its slope.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example xml:id="sec1-342-2-linear-ex1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the equation <m>2x + 5y = 8</m>. It is linear because we can isolate <m>y</m> and write the equation in the form <m>y = ax + b</m>; rewriting gives
        <md>
          <mrow>y = -\dfrac{2}{5}x + \dfrac{8}{5}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        If we want to find the <m>x-</m>intercept, we can do so by setting <m>y = f(x) = 0</m>. This gives: 
        <md>
          <mrow>0 \amp = -\dfrac{2}{5}x + \dfrac{8}{5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\dfrac{2}{5}x \amp = \dfrac{8}{5} </mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp = 4 </mrow>
        </md>
        So the <m>x-</m>intercept occurs at <m>(4,0)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the <m>y-</m>intercept, we need to find <m>f(0)</m>. This means we plug in 0 to the equation:
        <md>
          <mrow>f(0) = -\dfrac{2}{5}(0) + \dfrac{8}{5} = \dfrac{8}{5}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Since the slope is the value of the constant <m>a</m> when the equation is in the form <m>y = ax + b</m>, and we know that <m>y = -\dfrac{2}{5}x + \dfrac{8}{5}</m>, the slope is <m>a = -\dfrac{2}{5}</m>. This tells us that when creating the line, to move from one point to another, we must go down two units and right five units. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    Things to discuss:
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          constant functions
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          slope-intercept form
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          point-slope form
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          equation of vertical/horizontal lines
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          profit, revenue, cost
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          average rate of change
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          computing linear regressions
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</section>